The govern- ment and revenues of the different provinces were divided between the emperor and the senate. The other imperial provinces of any considerable importance were governed by leqati C'aeE'aris, taken from those who had been consuls or praetors, or from the senators, and their finances managed by procurators, who were either knights or freedmen3 but Egypt was governed by a prefect (see 3:74), ap- pointed by the emperor from the knights, with the powers of its former kings (loco regum).
